We had a really enjoyable evening! The atmosphere was great and the decor is amazing. The staff were friendly and efficient. I am not the biggest sushi fan, but the food was delicious! Great cocktails and mocktails too.

We got lucky on an early Monday evening without a reservation otherwise I would recommend a reservation. We ate on the second floor, very lovely and cozy tropical floral decor. We had Shrimp Gyoza as an appetizer and Tenno Ninko as a main. As for desert we had passion fruit/mango and strawberry cheesecake mochi. There were 2 of us and we couldn’t finish all the food so for 2 people it was plenty. We were very satisfied and would definitely visit again. Probably the best mochi we’ve ever had. The staff was very accommodating, even tho we didn’t have a reservation and gave us a window seat as requested.

Had a really disappointing dinner here. Ordered the shrimp gyoza but the skin on the outside was mushy. It was definitely not served right after it was prepared. Ordered 2 individual sushi plates and it turned out as disappointing. Rice on the sushi was too cold and hard, it was probably prepared before hand and they just plate it nicely when orders came in. Fish was fresh at all, wrong of me to think that a restaurant located in a city would be able to serve fresh food.

Service was great though, waiters were friendly and it was a nice ambience. Pity the food was not up to standard.

The service was impeccable! I love sushi, so I went into the shop for takeout with a polite/enthusiastic attitude. The waitress and manager returned the comfy feeling back tenfold!
First, they helped me order online and apply the coupon code I found. Then, I was encouraged to sit for approximately 5 minutes as the chefs rolled the sushi. Although my order was takeout, the manager amicably welcomed me to explore the restaurant. Three of the pictures below show the decor, interesting and plentiful.
There are a lot of restaurants along the Reuss, but the Reuss is as insect-infested as it is beautiful. Negishi Luzern is a block away from all the spiders and flying bugs, which means cleaner and therefore safer food.
It's also worth noting that the first floor is fairly empty, while the second floor is packed. So although it may not seem so from the outside, business is good here.
While service and atmosphere are important, the taste of the food makes it or breaks it, yeah? After having eaten sushi throughout the United States and Canada, I'd say that Negishi's options range from a 7/10 to 10/10. The best was Japanese Garden, followed by the Levantin. I ate those rolls so quickly that they were gone before I could take close-up pictures! Inari Nigiri was a tasty balance of sweet and flavourful. Salmon Summer was filling and fresh.
Not worth recommending: Rainbow Mango, Maki Vegi Mix, and Avocado Nigiri. The mango is there for crunch, not juiciness. The 1-ingredient sushi have a get 'em full rice-to-filling ratio typically found in buffets.
The two end pieces of the 8 Stk. specialty roll had rice-predominant centres, but the middle pieces have a generous amount of filling. If you view the menu prices as expensive, this might be frustrating. If you just want a break from Switzerland's overdose of cheese, chocolate, burgers, Italian fare, sausages, etc., Negishi is the perfect break.
